                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>A special note should be made about the forms of the letter "a"
                           throughout. The scribe renders "a," when not in the initial position of a
                           line, in three forms: a two-bow form that is indented slightly, which can
                           be seen in "and" in line seven of the first stanza, a closed-bow form
                           without indenting, as can be seen in "and" at line two of the same
                           stanza, and a slightly more indented vesion where the lower bow is larger
                           than the upper, which can be seen in "amerous" in the first line of
                           stanza five. Whether this is majuscule or miniscule seems dependant on
                           line height, but the scribe is inconsistent regarding their line heights
                           so it's not easy to determine which is intended at particular locations.
                           For this reason I've chosen to render tham all as miniscule.</p>
                        <p>Majuscule "a" is also rendered in one of three forms if we assume the
                           initial glyph of each line is intended to be majuscule -- which I am not
                           sure can accurately determined. There is a form that is similar to the
                           variable line-height form mentioned above, a form that is similar to this
                           form but with a much deeper bow (as can be seen in "as" in the second
                           line of the second stanza of folio 47), a form with a flattened upper bow
                           and angular lower bow (as can be seen in "A geyn" at line three of that
                           same stanza), a form that is similar to an "A" compressed on both sides
                           (as can be seen in the initial line of the first stanza of folio 50
                           verso) and a form that is similar to the variable line-height form but
                           with a much more pronounced lower bow and deeper indentation (as can been
                           in "and" at line two of the first stanza of folio 48 verso). </p>
                     </handNote>
